THE DEFAULT SETTING: DIO1 ~ 8 are all INPUT

Note: The DIO protocol will reset to the default setting after a cold boot.

1. Command Format
   # i2cset -f -y <i2c_num> <device_addr> <reg_addr> <value>
   # i2cget -f -y <i2c_num> <device_addr> <reg_addr>

   [Example]:
	<i2c_num>: 1
	<device_adrr>: 0x22
	<reg_addr>: 0x00~0x03 (as below picture)
	<value>:
		- Bit0 -> DIO1, Low: 0 High: 1
		- Bit1 -> DIO2, Low: 0 High: 1
		  ...
		-Bit7 -> DIO8, Low: 0 High: 1


2. DIO Output sample code
   # i2cset -f -y 1 0x22 0x01 0xFF	//Set DIO1 ~ 8 as High
   # i2cset -f -y 1 0x22 0x03 0x00	//Set DIO1 ~ 8 as Output
   # i2cset -f -y 1 0x22 0x01 0xF0	//Set DIO1 ~ 4 as Low and DIO5~8 as High
   # i2cset -f -y 1 0x22 0x01 0x01	//Set DIO1 as High and DIO2~8 as Low
   # i2cset -f -y 1 0x22 0x03 0x0F	//Set DIO1 ~ 4 as Input and DIO5~8 as Output
   ...

3. DIO input sample code
   # i2cset -f -y 1 0x22 0x03 0xFF	//Set DIO1 ~ 8 as Input
   # i2cget -f -y 1 0x22 0x00		//Read all inputs
